hough often hard, children’s lives reflected a hopeful and expanding future, and their letters recount their skills and determination as well as family lore and community histories. Children both make and participate in history, but until recently their role has been largely ignored. In “I Want to Join Your Club,” Lewis provides direct evidence that children’s lives, like adults’, have both continuity and change and form part of the warp and woof of the social fabric.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLetters to the editorzCanada. 0aRural childrenzCanadavCorrespondence. 0aRural childrenzNewfoundland and LabradorvCorrespondence. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aLife Writing. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aLewis, Norah L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920730140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207301/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles